  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I find an engine for an SAE Supra?",
  "response": "Finding an engine for an SAE Supra (the Society of Automotive Engineers' automotive engineering competitions) involves several steps. The SAE Supra is typically a small-scale racing vehicle designed by student teams, and sourcing an engine depends on the specific rules and requirements of your competition. Here are steps to help you find an engine:\n\n1. **Check Rules and Regulations**: First, review the rules and regulations of the SAE competition you are participating in. There might be specific guidelines regarding engine types, size, displacement, and allowable modifications.\n\n2. **Identify Compatible Engines**: Based on the competition rules, identify which engines are eligible. Common options for small-scale race cars include motorcycle engines, small automotive engines (like those found in compact cars), and specially designed racing engines.\n\n3. **Source Engines**:\n   - **Local Auto Parts Stores**: Check with local auto parts suppliers for available engines. They might direct you to salvage yards or new engine suppliers.\n   - **Salvage Yards**: Visit or contact local junkyards or salvage yards where you can find used engines at a lower cost.\n   - **Online Marketplaces**: Websites like eBay, Craigslist, and Facebook Marketplace often have listings for used engines. Be sure to check the condition and details before purchasing.\n   - **Specialty Racing Suppliers**: Some companies specialize in racing parts and might have engines that fit your needs. They can provide advice on what engine to choose for your vehicle.\n\n4. **Consider Engine Performance**: When selecting an engine, consider not only availability but also performance characteristics like power output, weight, and ease of installation.\n\n5. **Consult with Your Team**: Discuss options with your teammates or advisors. They might have insights or contacts that could help in finding the right engine.\n\n6. **Seek Help from Alumni/Faculty**: If you're part of a university team, reach out to faculty or alumni who may have experience in sourcing engines for SAE competitions. They could offer valuable advice or connections.\n\n7. **Participate in Forums and Groups**: Join SAE and automotive forums or groups on social media. Engaging with the community can lead to recommendations and potential leads on sourcing engines.\n\n8. **Consider Custom Solutions**: If you can't find an engine that meets your criteria, discuss the option of custom solutions with your team. Sometimes modifying an existing engine or working with a local machinist can yield good results.\n\nAfter gathering all the necessary information, make a final decision based on your team\u2019s goals, budget, and competition requirements.",
